Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.190 --> 00:00:05.950
Katie &gt;&gt; Welcome everyone, thanks for coming
to an Authors at Google talk featuring Thomas

00:00:05.950 --> 00:00:11.530
Goetz. We're really excited to have you here.
Thomas Goetz is executive editor at Wired

00:00:11.530 --> 00:00:16.410
Magazine and has more then 15 years of experience
in Journalism having worked at the Village

00:00:16.410 --> 00:00:21.210
Voice, The Wall Street Journal, and the Industry
Standard. He frequently writes about science,

00:00:21.210 --> 00:00:26.010
health, and medicine and he has a Master of
Public Health degree from UC Berkeley. He

00:00:26.010 --> 00:00:31.360
is not a doctor though but even given that,
he's written that things that kills us today

00:00:31.360 --> 00:00:36.230
aren't infections or epidemics. They are diseases
of lifestyle, in other words, more than half

00:00:36.230 --> 00:00:41.949
of us are the agents of our own demise which
sounds kind of scary but he's actually pretty

00:00:41.949 --> 00:00:46.859
optimistic about healthcare. He's here today
to talk about "The Decision Tree" and his

00:00:46.859 --> 00:00:51.370
main sort of argument is that the more people
see themselves as decision makers in their

00:00:51.370 --> 00:00:55.980
own healthcare, the better their behavior
and outcomes, and he also talks a lot about

00:00:55.980 --> 00:01:01.609
how technology can help people control their
health better. So, we have discounted books

00:01:01.609 --> 00:01:06.680
so after the talk if you'd like to go purchase
one and speak to Mr. Goetz, he will gladly

00:01:06.680 --> 00:01:13.860
sign a copy for you as well and then if you
have any questions, we have a mic here after

00:01:13.860 --> 00:01:18.500
the talk. Please feel free to come up and
ask so with that, please welcome Thomas Goetz.

00:01:18.500 --> 00:01:19.500
[applause]

00:01:19.500 --> 00:01:31.130
Thomas Goetz &gt;&gt; Thanks. So you guys don't
have to stay so far back. If you come closer,

00:01:31.130 --> 00:01:35.880
it's easier for me but, your choice. So I'm
very happy to be here at Google to talk about

00:01:35.880 --> 00:01:42.090
this. I actually um-- A lot of these ideas
that are in the book were hashed out,

00:01:42.090 --> 00:01:47.660
some of them, in this very room when I would
come to SciFoo over the last few years which

00:01:47.660 --> 00:01:55.240
is a little conference that Google and Nature
and O'Reilly put together, so it's fun to

00:01:55.240 --> 00:02:01.490
be here to talk about the same ideas again.
What I wanted to talk about today was this

00:02:01.490 --> 00:02:07.360
idea of, you know, there's been a lot of discussion,
especially of late, about a healthcare crisis

00:02:07.360 --> 00:02:13.910
and a need for healthcare reform in the US.
There is also--, that is true and it needs

00:02:13.910 --> 00:02:21.780
addressing and we need to engage our government
in providing coverage for people and making

00:02:21.780 --> 00:02:26.200
sure everyone has access to healthcare, but
there's another issue involved which is not

00:02:26.200 --> 00:02:35.790
so much a healthcare crisis as a health crisis
which is happening in the country and basically

00:02:35.790 --> 00:02:41.670
that as Katie alluded to, we are making all
sorts of decisions that lead to consequences

00:02:41.670 --> 00:02:48.990
that really doesn't have to work out that
way. We're making poor decisions, poorly informed

00:02:48.990 --> 00:02:55.410
decisions, that basically lead to a consequence
of poor health and I just want to explain

00:02:55.410 --> 00:03:01.349
that and discuss that a little bit today.
So, there's no end of health information,

00:03:01.349 --> 00:03:08.120
right? There's no end of access to information
about our health. We are inundated with a

00:03:08.120 --> 00:03:10.990
cacophony of information in fact, we are barraged
with a stern list of things we should do and

00:03:10.990 --> 00:03:17.900
shouldn't do, mostly shouldn't do, and the
trick is we don't actually do them. Only three

00:03:17.900 --> 00:03:23.600
percent of Americans manage to pull off four
basic health behaviors, behaviors that any

00:03:23.600 --> 00:03:28.090
one of you would probably be able to
recite off if I put you to it but they are

00:03:28.090 --> 00:03:33.849
to not smoke, maintain a healthy body weight,
get some regular exercise, and don't drink

00:03:33.849 --> 00:03:40.739
too much. So only three percent of Americans
manage to do all four of those behaviors consistently,

00:03:40.739 --> 00:03:45.160
which is pretty startling. What it means is
that we are basically somehow

00:03:45.160 --> 00:03:49.090
disengaged from all that information that
is coming at us. We don't really have a way

00:03:49.090 --> 00:03:55.239
to put it into an action and what happens
is that we are not only making poor decisions

00:03:55.239 --> 00:04:01.459
for ourselves but we're making poor decisions
for our families and we are failing to act

00:04:01.459 --> 00:04:06.879
when we can, when we have these little moments
of making choices we are making the wrong

00:04:06.879 --> 00:04:11.150
choices. We think our health doesn't matter,
health too often is something that we decide

00:04:11.150 --> 00:04:16.299
that we don't want to engage in and that is
somehow a source of anxiety or fear for many

00:04:16.299 --> 00:04:19.900
people, for many Americans. For these people,
that's probably the case, right? You don't

00:04:19.900 --> 00:04:26.470
want to think about it. I think that's unfortunate
and it's not the way it needs to be. What

00:04:26.470 --> 00:04:32.220
happens in practice, what's happening in this
country is that we are getting a series of

00:04:32.220 --> 00:04:39.340
decisions are cascading to more and more serious
conditions so you have what I call a "cascade

00:04:39.340 --> 00:04:44.310
of cormorbidities". You have one disease leading
to the other disease leading to the next disease

00:04:44.310 --> 00:04:50.460
and this is the way most of us get sick and
die in this country. In fact, seventy percent

00:04:50.460 --> 00:04:58.150
of Americans die of chronic disease, so these
are diseases that are not infectious diseases,

00:04:58.150 --> 00:05:04.090
these are not diseases that come out of the
blue, they are diseases that slowly build

00:05:04.090 --> 00:05:09.710
and it's the deterioration of health. Likewise,
seventy percent of the money that we spend

00:05:09.710 --> 00:05:14.380
on healthcare in this country is spent on
managing chronic diseases. So when you look

00:05:14.380 --> 00:05:19.600
at healthcare reform and where we should be
directing some of the issues of reforming

00:05:19.600 --> 00:05:24.680
the cost side, well this is part of the problem,
right? It's that these chronic diseases are

00:05:24.680 --> 00:05:30.820
causing us to spend too much money to keep
people alive when they have already had a

00:05:30.820 --> 00:05:36.550
disease beset themselves. It's not where we
want to be, and then of course you get this

00:05:36.550 --> 00:05:43.440
stat that was alluded to. 55 percent of Americans
die of something that can be traced back to

00:05:43.440 --> 00:05:48.800
a personal decision. This was a study done
by Ralph Keeney out of Duke University. He's

00:05:48.800 --> 00:05:54.530
an operations researcher which is one of these
fascinating disciplines. You've got, maybe

00:05:54.530 --> 00:06:00.150
some of you are in operations research, but
what he did is he took the kind of standard

00:06:00.150 --> 00:06:06.120
CDC data, right? The mortality data that the
CDC gathers on all of us and he analyzed it

00:06:06.120 --> 00:06:10.280
in a slightly different way. What he wanted
to do was see how many of the

00:06:10.280 --> 00:06:16.280
mortality statistics could be attributed if
you work your way back to a choice, when somebody

00:06:16.280 --> 00:06:21.070
had a choice. What he did was he excluded
some of the things that we don't necessarily

00:06:21.070 --> 00:06:25.960
think of as a choice such as getting in your
car, right? Getting in your car, we pretty

00:06:25.960 --> 00:06:30.150
much have to do that if we want to be a functioning
member of society, but getting in your car

00:06:30.150 --> 00:06:36.000
drunk or getting in your car and texting,
well that's a decision so those decisions

00:06:36.000 --> 00:06:41.010
would be ones that would fall under this 55
percent. It's startling when you think about

00:06:41.010 --> 00:06:47.150
it that if more than half of us are dying
because of these decisions, why are we making

00:06:47.150 --> 00:06:55.650
these decisions? Where do we lack this opportunity
to engage? Right. So that's a problem and

00:06:55.650 --> 00:07:00.270
that's the depressing part of the talk. What
I want to do now is turn towards this idea,

00:07:00.270 --> 00:07:06.889
what I actually think is a very helpful and
hopeful way of righting this wrong, particularly

00:07:06.889 --> 00:07:13.070
I want to talk about three experiments. These
are three experiments that are in the book

00:07:13.070 --> 00:07:19.380
that I think are, to me, offer a new structure
and new approach to our engagement with our

00:07:19.380 --> 00:07:26.539
health. The first experiment takes place in
London, on Whitehall Street. In the 1960's,

00:07:26.539 --> 00:07:32.070
in 1967, a couple of researchers from the
London School of Hygiene came to Whitehall

00:07:32.070 --> 00:07:37.100
Street and decided that this was the place
to conduct a unprecedented experiment. Whitehall

00:07:37.100 --> 00:07:41.199
Street is the epicenter of British government.
It is the equivalent of, when you say Whitehall

00:07:41.199 --> 00:07:46.729
in the UK it's the equivalent of saying Washington
here. At the end is Big Ben, that's the Halls

00:07:46.729 --> 00:07:50.889
of Parliament, around the corner is 10 Downing
Street, and up and down Whitehall Street are

00:07:50.889 --> 00:07:57.060
all the government offices, right? So the
Labor office, the Treasury, all the kind of

00:07:57.060 --> 00:08:01.150
offices of government. What's great, and what
made Whitehall especially in the 1960's such

00:08:01.150 --> 00:08:07.500
an important place to do a population study,
was that it was, as the researchers called,

00:08:07.500 --> 00:08:12.590
"exquisitely stratified". So you had through
the ranks of the civil service, through the

00:08:12.590 --> 00:08:18.400
ranks of people who worked on Whitehall, you
had five distinct categories. You had an executive

00:08:18.400 --> 00:08:23.530
class, an administrative class, a clerical
class--, No, I'm sorry. an executive, an administrative,

00:08:23.530 --> 00:08:27.930
a professional, a clerical, and at the bottom
was another category; these were the messengers,

00:08:27.930 --> 00:08:34.740
the janitors who kind of did all the work
that was left for them.

00:08:34.740 --> 00:08:39.899
What the researchers found was that, let me
back up, they specifically wanted to study

00:08:39.899 --> 00:08:44.900
the causes, not the causes of heart disease
but who was most likely to get heart disease,

00:08:44.900 --> 00:08:49.290
so that's why they were drawn to Whitehall
Street because they had this great stratification

00:08:49.290 --> 00:08:55.640
by class. So what they found was that the
people at the bottom of the group, of the

00:08:55.640 --> 00:09:00.060
18,000 people, the people at the bottom had
four times the risk of dying of heart disease

00:09:00.060 --> 00:09:06.520
as the people at the to. So there was something
really negative about being at the bottom

00:09:06.520 --> 00:09:11.150
and there was something protective about being
at the top. Well, we could all imagine what

00:09:11.150 --> 00:09:15.750
some of these things are, right? So it looked
like the people at the bottom tended to smoke

00:09:15.750 --> 00:09:21.980
a little bit more, people at the bottom tended
to not have as healthy a diet, they tended

00:09:21.980 --> 00:09:26.620
to be a little heavier, so those were known
risks for heart disease and so they factored

00:09:26.620 --> 00:09:31.750
all those things out of the study but they
were still left with this profound relation

00:09:31.750 --> 00:09:39.170
between status and heart disease. The people
at the bottom now, with all the factors excluded,

00:09:39.170 --> 00:09:42.560
all the known factors excluded, the people
at the bottom are still twice as likely to

00:09:42.560 --> 00:09:47.320
die of heart disease at the people at the
top, and there was no known reason for this

00:09:47.320 --> 00:09:52.711
association so it was pretty stunning.
They didn't know what to make of it. They

00:09:52.711 --> 00:09:57.410
thought at first that maybe there was something
protective about being in the upper classes,

00:09:57.410 --> 00:10:01.501
maybe there was some genetic inbreeding that
maybe protected you if you were part of the

00:10:01.501 --> 00:10:06.990
aristocracy or the elite, that didn't hold
water for very long.

00:10:06.990 --> 00:10:13.330
So what they were left with was the idea that
maybe status in and of itself was the correlation,

00:10:13.330 --> 00:10:19.740
maybe status was the driver towards good or
bad health. They distilled it to this idea

00:10:19.740 --> 00:10:24.050
of control of destiny, that the people at
the bottom had very little control of their

00:10:24.050 --> 00:10:29.709
destiny. When they made decisions, they were
only somewhat likely to come true because

00:10:29.709 --> 00:10:33.421
they were subject to all the other decisions
of everybody above them while the people at

00:10:33.421 --> 00:10:38.170
the very top, they made a decision and that
was pretty much the way things went, right?

00:10:38.170 --> 00:10:42.920
They were in control and the people at the
bottom had very little control and we all

00:10:42.920 --> 00:10:47.769
know what this feels like. I mean, the people
we deal with these kind of ideas all the time.

00:10:47.769 --> 00:10:51.060
When we call customer service, those are people
at the bottom, right?

00:10:51.060 --> 00:10:55.170
So when we call customer service and they
can't help us with our cell phone plan, we

00:10:55.170 --> 00:10:59.510
say, "Can I speak to your supervisor?" And
they can't help so we say, "Can we speak to

00:10:59.510 --> 00:11:02.540
your supervisor?", and we go up and up the
chain until we get somebody who can make a

00:11:02.540 --> 00:11:06.209
decision, right? Somebody who has some control,
somebody who has some authority. Likewise,

00:11:06.209 --> 00:11:09.580
we know what it's like to be at the other
end of the spectrum, we know what it's like

00:11:09.580 --> 00:11:13.670
to have control. We know what it's like to
be, you know we have all these phrases, when

00:11:13.670 --> 00:11:20.120
we're in the flow we're in the top our game,
we are surfing the wave, this is a good feeling,

00:11:20.120 --> 00:11:27.640
we like to be in control. So, the second experiment
that I want to talk about takes place in the

00:11:27.640 --> 00:11:33.310
bathroom, particularly it takes place in 5,000
bathrooms around the country. There was this

00:11:33.310 --> 00:11:37.180
great research study that's ongoing out of
Brown University and it's called the National

00:11:37.180 --> 00:11:41.350
Weight Control Registry and what they've done
is they've selected 5,000

00:11:41.350 --> 00:11:46.430
people, 5,000 Americans, who have successfully
lost weight. They've lost at least thirty

00:11:46.430 --> 00:11:51.279
pounds and kept it off for at least a year
and so basically if you want to study what

00:11:51.279 --> 00:11:56.970
are the secrets to losing weight, these are
the people you want to talk to, right? So

00:11:56.970 --> 00:12:00.280
they asked them, they've surveyed them for
all the tricks that they might have, all their

00:12:00.280 --> 00:12:04.330
behaviors, everything that they do, they've
given them surveys after surveys. And what

00:12:04.330 --> 00:12:08.060
they found is a lot of the things that you
might expect. They tend to exercise a little

00:12:08.060 --> 00:12:13.310
more than the average person and they tend
to watch what they eat a little better, so

00:12:13.310 --> 00:12:17.190
they have better nutritional choices. You
might have heard that when you tend to eat

00:12:17.190 --> 00:12:22.420
at breakfast regularly, that it actually correlates
with maintaining a health body weight, that's

00:12:22.420 --> 00:12:27.019
comes out of the National Weight Control Registry.
But one of the other things they found that

00:12:27.019 --> 00:12:32.790
was quite surprising that they didn't expect
to find at all was the simple fact that the

00:12:32.790 --> 00:12:38.670
people who successfully lost weight stepped
on a scale a lot. In fact, 80 percent of them

00:12:38.670 --> 00:12:43.500
stepped on a scale at least once a day, and
50 percent--, I'm sorry 80 percent of them

00:12:43.500 --> 00:12:46.950
stepped on a scale at least once a week, 50
percent of them stepped on a scale once a

00:12:46.950 --> 00:12:52.510
day like this woman, Jody Green, who every
day steps on a scale, takes a picture of it,

00:12:52.510 --> 00:12:59.709
and posts it on Flickr with a fancy pair of
socks. What they've all realized is that this

00:12:59.709 --> 00:13:06.649
tracking, this idea of monitoring their progress,
is a very powerful, helpful way to engage

00:13:06.649 --> 00:13:12.270
in successful behavior change. Now it's known
by the phrase, in public health they call

00:13:12.270 --> 00:13:16.420
it feedback, right? So when you get people
involved in a feedback loop and you help them

00:13:16.420 --> 00:13:21.000
monitor their progress, they tend to be able
to successfully or have better success at

00:13:21.000 --> 00:13:26.670
changing their behavior. Now you combine this
feedback loop with the idea of groups and

00:13:26.670 --> 00:13:30.560
you get even more potential for change so
this is the secret in fact of Weight Watchers,

00:13:30.560 --> 00:13:35.730
right? I don't know if, when I started this
project I was actually very skeptical of Weight

00:13:35.730 --> 00:13:39.130
Watchers. What it turns out is that it's one
of the few diet programs that actually works

00:13:39.130 --> 00:13:43.130
because they give you feedback, they have
this point system that some of you may have

00:13:43.130 --> 00:13:48.700
heard of that basically translates the nutritional
information box on the cereal and the food

00:13:48.700 --> 00:13:53.410
products into a formula that gives you a number
of points that you're allowed and that's a

00:13:53.410 --> 00:13:57.459
very simple way of getting people involved
in this feedback loop. Likewise, they have

00:13:57.459 --> 00:14:00.721
these meetings, right? With Weight Watchers,
they go to the meeting. They call it the magic

00:14:00.721 --> 00:14:03.680
of the meeting and when you're able to share
your information, when you are able to share

00:14:03.680 --> 00:14:08.730
your progress and track and compare your progress
with other people's progress, it turns out

00:14:08.730 --> 00:14:13.750
to be an effective way to change behavior.
so that's what we get out of the National

00:14:13.750 --> 00:14:21.980
Weight Control Registry. The third experiment
that I wanted to offer today takes us to Kansas

00:14:21.980 --> 00:14:28.210
City, Missouri and an orthodontic clinic.
There was an orthodontic clinic a few years

00:14:28.210 --> 00:14:34.389
ago that, as many orthodontists do, they deal
with teenagers, lots of adolescents who have

00:14:34.389 --> 00:14:40.130
braces and what they had was a group of kind
of incorrigibles who wouldn't brush their

00:14:40.130 --> 00:14:47.800
teeth. They had these kids who had just really
bad oral hygiene. So they--, in fact, they

00:14:47.800 --> 00:14:51.889
had to, this is the way that you monitor this
is to take photographs of your teeth and then

00:14:51.889 --> 00:14:57.430
you can analyze it for plaque coverage, so
they had forty kids who had about 70 percent

00:14:57.430 --> 00:15:02.540
of their tooth surface was covered with plaque,
right? So 70 percent was the baseline. They

00:15:02.540 --> 00:15:07.950
took-- they split the forty kids into two
groups, one, they said, they brought them

00:15:07.950 --> 00:15:11.480
into the office and said, "We'd like you be
part of this study with this new experimental

00:15:11.480 --> 00:15:15.709
toothpaste", so they gave them the toothpaste
and it said experimental in big, black letters

00:15:15.709 --> 00:15:20.250
on the side and they said, "Go home and brush
your teeth like we'd told you before. Brush

00:15:20.250 --> 00:15:23.630
your teeth twice a day, two minutes a day."
They even gave them a little kitchen timer

00:15:23.630 --> 00:15:28.220
to time it, "and come back in three months."
So that was the experimental group. The control

00:15:28.220 --> 00:15:32.420
group were twenty kids who were members of
the clinic but they didn't tell them they

00:15:32.420 --> 00:15:37.829
were going to be an experiment. They had signed
a kind of blanket waiver as a patient of the

00:15:37.829 --> 00:15:40.490
clinic so they didn't have
to tell them they were going to be in the

00:15:40.490 --> 00:15:45.040
experiment, they were just on track to come
back in three months anyway. So after three

00:15:45.040 --> 00:15:49.579
months, you can imagine where this is going,
after three months the kids in the experimental

00:15:49.579 --> 00:15:54.600
group had profoundly improved dental hygiene.
It's not going to sound that profound but

00:15:54.600 --> 00:15:59.019
their coverage had gone from 70 percent down
to 50 percent which was, actually after three

00:15:59.019 --> 00:16:02.519
months, considered quite good progress. The
control group meanwhile, their hygiene had

00:16:02.519 --> 00:16:08.040
actually gotten a little worse. They had ticked
up to nearly 80 percent coverage so there

00:16:08.040 --> 00:16:11.490
was a real significant difference, right?
At least 30 percent difference between the

00:16:11.490 --> 00:16:15.779
control group and the experimental group.
The question is what was in that toothpaste?

00:16:15.779 --> 00:16:20.769
What was the secret toothpaste that they gave?
Well, it was Crest with fluoride, right? It

00:16:20.769 --> 00:16:26.050
was ordinary Crest. The magic wasn't in the
toothpaste at all, it was in the fact that

00:16:26.050 --> 00:16:30.220
these kids were in an experiment and they
knew they were in an experiment, so no doubt

00:16:30.220 --> 00:16:34.910
some of you already know what this is called.
This is called the Hawthorne Effect. It's

00:16:34.910 --> 00:16:39.540
named after this kind of mythical study that
was done in the 1920's by Western Electric

00:16:39.540 --> 00:16:44.050
Company. They wanted to see if they could
get their workers to be more productive, so

00:16:44.050 --> 00:16:49.110
they would experiment with the lighting in
the factory. They were making relays and when

00:16:49.110 --> 00:16:53.269
they would raise the lights to see if they
made more relays or they would lower the lights

00:16:53.269 --> 00:16:56.880
to see if they would make more relays. It
turned out when they did either one, lights

00:16:56.880 --> 00:17:00.949
went up, lights went down, they made more
relays because when the lights change, the

00:17:00.949 --> 00:17:06.350
workers knew that the experiment was on so
this has become kind of the mythical way of

00:17:06.350 --> 00:17:10.899
describing this phenomenon that when people
are under observation, they tend to change

00:17:10.899 --> 00:17:15.319
their behavior. So it's related to placebo
effect, it's the same thing that you see Heisenberg

00:17:15.319 --> 00:17:18.629
uncertainty principle, these are kind of well
known phenomena throughout the sciences. They

00:17:18.629 --> 00:17:25.759
are particularly vexing with experiments that
involved human subjects so during clinical

00:17:25.759 --> 00:17:32.029
trials for drugs, for instance, the Hawthorne
Effect is this thing that researchers try

00:17:32.029 --> 00:17:36.729
to accommodate and try to kind of factor out.
There are all sorts of ways of trying to get

00:17:36.729 --> 00:17:40.539
ride of the Hawthorne Effect. What was really
interesting about these orthodontists in Kansas

00:17:40.539 --> 00:17:44.840
City was they decided what happens if we try
to put the Hawthorne Effect to work? What

00:17:44.840 --> 00:17:50.809
happens if we try to put it to work and engage
people in the idea that they're in an experiment

00:17:50.809 --> 00:17:55.940
and it turned out to work. So what do we do
with this? What do we do with these three

00:17:55.940 --> 00:18:00.389
experiments? The idea
of control of destiny from Whitehall, the

00:18:00.389 --> 00:18:04.330
idea of feedback in groups that we've gotten
out of the National Weight Control Registry,

00:18:04.330 --> 00:18:12.240
and then this idea of making your life an
experiment out of the orthodontic clinic in

00:18:12.240 --> 00:18:20.679
Kansas City? To me, it becomes, in essence,
an algorithm, which being at Google makes

00:18:20.679 --> 00:18:27.379
sense to talk about. It's a formula that we
can actually use to start being more active,

00:18:27.379 --> 00:18:32.019
more engaged in monitoring our health, start
taking some control of our health. If we can

00:18:32.019 --> 00:18:37.419
use the opportunity to monitor where we are,
chart our progress, compare it to other people,

00:18:37.419 --> 00:18:42.109
actively use the data that we are generating
all the time every day in our lives and in

00:18:42.109 --> 00:18:48.359
our health, we can actually start to engage
with that information and have some control

00:18:48.359 --> 00:18:52.570
even though in the other senses of our lives,
it we may not feel like we do have a great

00:18:52.570 --> 00:18:55.809
dealof control.
It turns out that other research has borne

00:18:55.809 --> 00:19:00.440
this out as well. When you give people, when
you give patients, an opportunity to participate

00:19:00.440 --> 00:19:05.710
in their care, when they are simply involved
in the decision making, their averages, their

00:19:05.710 --> 00:19:11.629
outcomes on average tend to get much better.
In fact, they tend to get about 20 to 25 percent

00:19:11.629 --> 00:19:16.590
better then people who aren't involved in
the decision making. So it's also auspicious

00:19:16.590 --> 00:19:22.289
that I'm talking to you guys about this because
this idea of feedback in groups as powerful

00:19:22.289 --> 00:19:28.529
members or powerful drivers of behavior
change, can be pretty much easily translated

00:19:28.529 --> 00:19:34.570
into the terms data and social networks, right?
They are almost analogous terms and the fact

00:19:34.570 --> 00:19:40.200
is that even though public health researchers
have known for many years that feedback in

00:19:40.200 --> 00:19:44.190
groups are good ways of getting people to
engage behavior change, it hasn't been that

00:19:44.190 --> 00:19:48.649
easy, right? So you have to go through all
these kind of fancy research studies or you

00:19:48.649 --> 00:19:52.350
have to sign up with a program like Weight
Watchers, there's a lot of friction involved

00:19:52.350 --> 00:19:56.940
in getting people to actually go through the
process of feedback and behavior change. But

00:19:56.940 --> 00:20:00.950
if you translate it into data and social networks,
if you start using information technologies

00:20:00.950 --> 00:20:05.610
to tap into these same ideas, it becomes a
lot easier. There is far less friction involved,

00:20:05.610 --> 00:20:13.220
it's far more easy for anybody to get access
to these tools and strategies. This to me

00:20:13.220 --> 00:20:18.840
is what makes it so auspicious, that we're
at this moment in our healthcare system when

00:20:18.840 --> 00:20:23.109
we can start developing new tools and new
strategies to work on these principles and

00:20:23.109 --> 00:20:29.499
start engaging people in their health. So
one way that this looks, one way that this

00:20:29.499 --> 00:20:36.419
