00:24:50.570 --> 00:24:56.080
online calculators that help people understand
the risks and benefits of every different

00:24:56.080 --> 00:25:01.409
chemotherapy guiding them to what is hopefully
an informed choice in correlation, in association

00:25:01.409 --> 00:25:06.859
with their doctor of course. It turns out
that this meta analysis showed that again,

00:25:06.859 --> 00:25:11.080
when people are given these decision tools,
when they are given an opportunity to actually

00:25:11.080 --> 00:25:16.169
make decisions for their health and for their
choices, even not just preventive decisions

00:25:16.169 --> 00:25:21.499
but treatment decisions, care decisions, when
you are faced with a disease and really life

00:25:21.499 --> 00:25:28.250
or death stakes, the outcomes improve. The
third principle is as simple as this: every

00:25:28.250 --> 00:25:33.169
decision counts. So we are constantly making
decisions about our health, from those little

00:25:33.169 --> 00:25:37.739
micro decisions about where to park and how
far are we going to walk to work to what we

00:25:37.739 --> 00:25:41.840
are going to eat to whether we are going to
go to the gym that day. Every decision that

00:25:41.840 --> 00:25:47.229
we make adds up to our health, you know. We
set off on these trajectories of health basically

00:25:47.229 --> 00:25:53.440
and too often the approach is that it's kind
of fate is taking us on our course, right?

00:25:53.440 --> 00:26:00.039
That our health is something that we are not
necessarily in control of, we are not necessarily

00:26:00.039 --> 00:26:05.049
even participating in and I think that's exactly
wrong and that's what I'm hoping that people

00:26:05.049 --> 00:26:13.950
will start to realize, is that they become--,
we all are the drivers of our own health trajectories,

00:26:13.950 --> 00:26:19.809
and that's the essence of what I'm getting
at. Because as far as I'm concerned, it seems

00:26:19.809 --> 00:26:25.239
