00:39:10.220 --> 00:39:14.930
those decision tools that I mentioned like
that Lifemath.net. So when you are able to

00:39:14.930 --> 00:39:20.510
process your information and make those statistics
more specifically about you rather than about

00:39:20.510 --> 00:39:26.170
a generic average. That's one gesture. There
are some specific things that people are doing.

00:39:26.170 --> 00:39:30.800
There is a wonderful project out of Dartmouth
University a couple of researchers are trying

00:39:30.800 --> 00:39:37.960
to develop tools that make, for instance,
drug facts much easier to understand, so following

00:39:37.960 --> 00:39:42.750
the footsteps of the nutritional information
label, that kind of box, they are developing

00:39:42.750 --> 00:39:48.480
a drug facts box where all that kind of fine
print of the side effects and the risks of

00:39:48.480 --> 00:39:54.190
a drug that none of us can ever understand.
The drug facts box that they propose reduces

00:39:54.190 --> 00:40:00.349
that to very simple terms of who is this drug
for, what are the potential risks, what are

00:40:00.349 --> 00:40:04.119
the potential side effects, and what are the
odds that it is going to work for you. It's

00:40:04.119 --> 00:40:10.150
these very clearly stated, clearly presentative
information that help people understand exactly

00:40:10.150 --> 00:40:13.369
the pros and cons of a drug, and they've done
studies that have shown that people are much

00:40:13.369 --> 00:40:17.720
more, when they are given information, information
in that form, they are much better able to

00:40:17.720 --> 00:40:22.410
parse the information. More broadly, there's
some great work being done here at Google

00:40:22.410 --> 00:40:25.950
among other places in information design,
right? We are actually, in my mind, we are

00:40:25.950 --> 00:40:30.809
entering this golden age of information design
where we're understanding how to use graphical

00:40:30.809 --> 00:40:37.970
presentation of information to help people
understand. There is a lot of, this goes to

00:40:37.970 --> 00:40:42.450
kind of the behavioral economics approach
on this, is that people are irrational, right?

00:40:42.450 --> 00:40:46.549
And they can't understand numbers and even
they tend to make bad decisions even when

00:40:46.549 --> 00:40:52.849
they are given the good information. I don't
entirely buy that, I agree that it exists

00:40:52.849 --> 00:40:59.609
as a kind of status quo, but I don't buy that
that's where things end. There are a lot of

00:40:59.609 --> 00:41:05.920
efforts such as what's happening at Dartmouth,
such as what's happening. There's this other

00:41:05.920 --> 00:41:10.359
researcher at Cornell called Valerie Reyna
and she's come up with this theory called

00:41:10.359 --> 00:41:15.970
The Fuzzy-trace Theory. The idea is that yes,
when we give people just cold hard numbers

00:41:15.970 --> 00:41:21.299
and we ask them to just engage rationally,
they tend to mess up. They tend to generally

00:41:21.299 --> 00:41:26.569
not understand the numbers, but when you give
them a kind of fuzzy sense of what the numbers

00:41:26.569 --> 00:41:30.760
mean, she calls it the gist, when you give
them the sense of the gist of the data, where

00:41:30.760 --> 00:41:35.289
they are able to kind of draw on their emotional
intuitive reasoning skills as well as their

00:41:35.289 --> 00:41:39.410
rational reasoning skills, they tend to make
much better decisions. And so to me, that's

00:41:39.410 --> 00:41:45.029
incredibly hopeful, that kind of research
that you know it isn't this kind of cold duality

00:41:45.029 --> 00:41:48.681
between our emotional/rational, emotional
and rational selves, but actually that you

00:41:48.681 --> 00:41:54.210
can kind of use both of our sides of the brain
and help people understand information. I

00:41:54.210 --> 00:42:10.460
think that that holds great promise.

